ardie, France","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"AMIENS","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Ames  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ames","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Amis</i> or from the feminine form, <i>Amice</i>. The Old French word <i>amis</i>, is from Latin <i>amicus</i> ‘friend’, which was used in Late Latin as a term for a man of the lower classes, in particular a slave. There were also derivatives of this as personal names, in particular masculine <i>Amicius</i> and feminine <i>Amicia</i>. Both were in use as personal names in England and may have contributed to the surname.","German: perhaps a nickname for an active person, from an ancient Germanic word related to Old High German <i>amazzig</i> ‘busy’.","Dutch: possibly a patronymic from <i>Ame</i> a common personal name in Holland and Friesland, an abbreviated form of an ancient Germanic personal name, perhaps beginning with <i>amel</i> ‘strong’."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adèle D AMIENS was born in 0988, in Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Albéric de Coucy."},"et":{"988–":"0988–Surnud","0980–1020":"0980–1020","1008–1060":"1008–1060","1010–1079":"1010–1079","0988–Female":"0988–Surnud","1008":"1008","1079":"1079","0980":"0980","988":"0988","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1060":"1060","0988":"0988","Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Hauts-de-France, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffri